# Layout Rules

- Layouts must provide stable page structure first: header/title area, content container, and footer/adjacent sections should not jump when data or browser-only UI mounts.
- Reserve space for async or client-only regions inside layouts. If a sidebar, TOC, share block, ad slot, or media area loads later, keep a same-footprint placeholder or min-height container.
- Build mobile-first. Default to one-column flow, modest spacing, and readable widths on phones; expand to multi-column only when the desktop layout clearly improves scanability.
- Desktop enhancements must not degrade mobile usability. Avoid fixed widths that overflow on phones, and avoid dense side-by-side sections unless they collapse cleanly below `md`.
- Blog and list layouts should minimize CLS:
  - image slots need fixed aspect ratios or explicit dimensions
  - metadata/tags rows should wrap cleanly
  - pagination and filter controls should keep consistent height
- Post layouts should prioritize reading performance: constrained prose width, predictable heading spacing, and side content that degrades gracefully on smaller screens.
- Author and list layouts should prefer CSS grid/flex breakpoints over JS viewport logic.
- Keep layout components mostly presentational. Push data fetching, browser-only logic, and heavy interactivity down into leaf components or dedicated client islands.
- When touching layouts, verify both mobile and desktop rendering, because the same shell serves content-heavy and tool-heavy routes in this repo.
